<div class="container">
    <h1>Chapter Summary: Web Communication</h1>
    <p>This chapter introduced the fundamentals of web communication, including the roles of clients, servers, browsers, HTTP protocols, client-side and server-side operations, and APIs.</p>

    <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Client:</strong> Initiates requests and displays responses.</li>
        <li><strong>Server:</strong> Processes requests, manages resources, and sends responses.</li>
        <li><strong>Browser:</strong> Acts as the interface for the client to interact with web applications.</li>
        <li><strong>HTTP Protocol:</strong> The standard for request/response communication between client and server.</li>
        <li><strong>Client-Side Communication:</strong> Executes operations in the user’s browser (HTML, CSS, JavaScript).</li>
        <li><strong>Server-Side Communication:</strong> Handles operations on the server, interacts with databases, and generates responses.</li>
        <li><strong>APIs:</strong> Allow applications to exchange data programmatically.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Understanding these concepts is crucial for developing modern web applications and integrating different systems efficiently.</p>

